<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Dr</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0008</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ubmitted by Dr. Andrew Wilkins</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research Fellow in the School of Education at the University of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Roehampton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission draws upon interim findings from a three-year (2012-2015) Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC)-funded project investigating the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and practice of school governance and accountability in England today (Grant ref. ES/K001299/1).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Accountability is the condition of securing public trust and public agreement on the equitable and fair distribution of public resources. On these terms account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ability refers to the duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and responsibility of all state-funded institutions to manage themselves efficiently and equitably through public consultation and transparency, and in accordance with the law. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the specific case of converter and sponsor academies – schools with the flexibility and freedom to be administratively self-governing – and many other types of state-funded independent schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (e.g. free schools)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accountability is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not the strategic responsibility of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local government (though some risk assessment of academies is still performed by local government). Instead accountability is dispersed and devolved to boards of trustees (in the case of Multi-Academy and Umbrella Trust setups) and individual school governing bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – what we might call the new ‘middle-tier’ in state education. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department for Education (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) at this time emphasizes the role and responsibility of school governors in facilitating ‘effective governance’, through providing scrutiny of direction, enabling strategy and hol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ding head teachers and senior leaders to account. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But despite calls from the government, Ofsted and some school governor support services (e.g. The National Governors Association, NGA) to professionalize governing bodies en masse through increased training, support, self-evaluation, external inspection and exhaustive data provision, the task of how accountability can be best achieved in practice, within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the dynamics of governing bodies, lacks specificity and direction.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Across academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and even maintained schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school governors are very quickly coming to terms (however grudgingly in some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) with the reality of what school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">autonomy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> implies: increased responsibility to ensure effectiveness and continued improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the school. This is evident by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trends to professionalize and streamline the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role, remit and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> composition of the school governing body, e.g. prioritise skills-based appointments, reduce school governor numbers, weed out ‘amateur’ volunteers (considered ineffectual to the ‘business of schools’) and generate audit trails to evidence worth, performance and foster competition.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many school governors define their role in limited terms of providing risk, performance and finance assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and little else. The implication being that school governance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is reduced to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> practice and effect of technical efficiency. Performance-based evaluations led by Ofsted mean that school governors more than ever are forced to reorganize themselves as a response to targ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ets, indicators and evaluations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many school governors consider traditional s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">takeholder models of school governance (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">notably governance arrangements that make use of specialist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">civic knowledge and which are tied to a commitment to consensus through recognition of diversity of aims and perspectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as impractical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or secondary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the task of ensuring smooth managerial oversight of the school. The technical deman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ds placed on school governors (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specifically the need to periodically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upskill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, evidence worth through internal audit and external inspection, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> achievement and progression results against set targets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and so forth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) appear unsustainable from the point of view of many school governors. School governors feel exposed as subjects to be focused on, with both positive and negative repercussions. Positive in terms of ensuring more committed and able school governors are in place to hold schools to account for any mismanagement or underperformance; but equally negative in terms of exasperating an already beleaguered drive to recruit school governors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The capacity of some school governors to impact higher-order decision making in some Multi-Academy Trust (MAT) arrangements is completely absent in some cases. The agreements set out by some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MATs mean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> school governors on Local Governing Bodies (LGBs) have no statutory rights, e.g. rights enforceable through judicial review. School governors in effect are instructed simply to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘support’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">governance decisio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns already committed to by the board of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rustees. Under such governance arrangements school governors may express disappointment and frustration with having insufficient influence over hard governance decisions, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such as performance management and issues </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relating to welfare, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">finance and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> staffing. This can contribute negatively to generating mistrust on the governing body</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some school governors feeling like ‘token governors’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An issue raised by parents concerns the lack of governor visibility. Parents not represented on the school governing body frequently express interest in the utility and impact of the governing body – what are they for? The removal of any mandatory requirement for schools to produce an annual report for parents only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further removes the school governing body from the scope of parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Governor visibility is important in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erms of ensuring accountability and maintaining public trust. It can help also to assuage any parental fears or misimpressions and even </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tribute</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to a sense of shared ownership and vision of the school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of school governors today, as defined by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, is geared toward the strategic development and improvement of schools rather than the day-to-day operational planning and implementation of policy (the designated role of practitioners). Overall school governors identify strongly with this definition of their role, though the boundaries ostensibly dividing strategic and operational duties are often muddied and difficult to separate out in practice. One reason being that school governors can best hold head teachers and SLT to account when they have sufficient knowledge of both policy process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policy implementation. Governor school visits for example enable school governors to observe the direct impact and success of governance decision making (surely a true measure of effective governance and accountability), but without replicating the evaluative role of inspectors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government and Ofsted make clear what is to be expected of both maintained schools and academies in terms of ensuring accountability: school governors, ideally made up of ‘professionals’ (suitably qualified persons with substantive skills and knowledge), carry out the strategic function of performing regular and robust finance, performance and risk assessment. Increasingly narrow definitions of accountability pervade the performance and contribution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of school governors, including</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘consumer accountability’, e.g. strengthen consumer responsiveness and market position, foster school competition and market branding/impact.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">performative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> accountability’, e.g. performance management, responsiveness to arms-length regulatory bodies, targets, indicators and evaluations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘corporate accountability’, e.g. strengthen service efficiency, value for money, competitive tendering, emphasis on school survival, adaptability and flexibility.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Effective school governance lacks precise meaning. It is technical in scope (driven by the demands of internal audit and external inspection, target setting, performance management, benchmarks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> indicators, and so forth) but social in practice, in other words shaped by value conflicts and the beliefs, preferences and actions of individuals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Different schools operate on the basis of different legal structures, management conditio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns and funding arrangements, and will sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pursue and experiment with contrasting (and sometimes conflicting) approaches to governance on the basis of pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eferred values and principles. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The suggestion being that effective gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rnance is not an exact science but context driven and shape by cultures of governance. To be more precise effective governance is better performed when the head teacher and SLT including the chair are proficient in managing expectations, identifying existing skills and competencies, and challenging rather than ratifying blind loyalty, namely the tendency among some school governors to languish under the futility of presuming professional competence in their school leaders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Annual review report for parents to be made mandatory for all schools (again). Comprehensive, accessible and perhaps not written with Ofsted in mind (unlike most minutes from school governor meetings, agendas items and Head teachers report to school governors). The report would detail the impact of the school governing body in terms of school development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and improvement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> actively engaged in the appointment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MAT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trustees through election. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">imilar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">democratic, bottom-up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">model exists for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the establishment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Co-operative Trust schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The creation of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rea school boards or strategic area authorities with opportunities for genuine community involvement and issues to be deliberated and mediated through open and transparent discussion.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Performative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> capture – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the restless pursuit of squaring school policy with government policy and achievement and progression testing with Ofsted inspection – dominates much of what underpins school governance today. Beyond the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se concerns there needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">greater bottom-up accountability including the generation of mutual solutions to local need, greater public trust and a sense of shared ownership. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>